Stretch, twist, stop.

491
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:53,180
Stretch, twist, stop.

492
00:29:53,220 --> 00:29:54,500
Like frames in a movie.

493
00:29:54,500 --> 00:29:55,020
Yes.

494
00:29:55,480 --> 00:30:02,640
The Trotter-Cato theorem proves that as the time interval between these discrete amplet-wist events shrinks infinitesimally,

495
00:30:03,100 --> 00:30:07,200
the sequence converges into a continuous operator flow.

496
00:30:07,600 --> 00:30:12,440
So, while your neurobiology might be computing in discrete pulses,

497
00:30:13,260 --> 00:30:19,880
the experienced geometry within the RSVP field is a continuous fluid trajectory.

498
00:30:20,480 --> 00:30:24,160
I want to push back on this idea of continuous fluid flow for a second.

499
00:30:24,160 --> 00:30:24,860
Go for it.

500
00:30:24,860 --> 00:30:30,480
I understand the river analogy for things like writing or solving a step-by-step equation.

501
00:30:30,980 --> 00:30:35,320
But what about the moments when thought is entirely discontinuous?

502
00:30:35,760 --> 00:30:36,360
What do you mean?

503
00:30:36,360 --> 00:30:38,740
What if the river has a massive waterfall?

504
00:30:39,260 --> 00:30:41,560
I'm talking about sudden aha moments.

505
00:30:41,620 --> 00:30:41,960
Mm-hmm.

506
00:30:42,520 --> 00:30:43,320
An epiphany.

507
00:30:43,620 --> 00:30:43,920
Right.

508
00:30:44,100 --> 00:30:50,520
A leap of logic where you don't smoothly paddle from A to B, you're just suddenly at B.

509
00:30:50,880 --> 00:30:56,020
How does this field theory handle a massive discontinuous jump in the manifold?

510
00:30:56,740 --> 00:31:04,900
You're touching on a crucial limitation of the biological prior, which the paper formalizes in Appendix B as the coherence criterion.

511
00:31:05,080 --> 00:31:06,220
The coherence criterion.

512
00:31:06,220 --> 00:31:06,580
Yes.

513
00:31:06,700 --> 00:31:16,280
For a thought trajectory to be coherent and survivable, it must maintain low-phase misalignment, keep the raft pointed downstream, and low vorticity avoid whirlpools.

514
00:31:16,320 --> 00:31:16,600
Okay.

515
00:31:16,600 --> 00:31:27,120
If a cognitive task demands a massive discontinuous jump across the manifold going over the waterfall, that leap inherently generates a massive spike in entropy.

516
00:31:27,520 --> 00:31:35,100
Because there is no low-dimensional CPG grid to support a teleportation across the semantic space.

517
00:31:35,920 --> 00:31:37,120
It's too unpredictable.

518
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:37,880
Right.

519
00:31:38,040 --> 00:31:40,080
And we know what happens when entropy spikes.

520
00:31:40,520 --> 00:31:43,080
The exponential penalty formula kicks in.

521
00:31:43,580 --> 00:31:47,240
So the biological prior actively suppresses the thought.

522
00:31:47,520 --> 00:31:48,120
Yes.

523
00:31:48,120 --> 00:31:48,680
Wait.

524
00:31:48,800 --> 00:31:52,400
Are you saying the brain actively prevents us from having epiphanies?

525
00:31:52,520 --> 00:31:53,600
It suppresses the leap?

526
00:31:53,680 --> 00:31:58,480
It suppresses the unstructured leap, the raw, high-dimensional calculation.

527
00:31:58,760 --> 00:31:59,060
Wow.

528
00:31:59,340 --> 00:32:02,520
This is a profound realization about human cognition.

529
00:32:02,800 --> 00:32:07,280
We simply do not process meaning by teleporting across the manifold.

530
00:32:07,280 --> 00:32:09,580
So how do we ever get anywhere new?

531
00:32:10,020 --> 00:32:16,460
If a massive non-compositional jump is required, the human brain will often fail to make the connection.

532
00:32:17,060 --> 00:32:25,780
Or, as we will discuss when we look at the experimental data later, the brain will invent a slower structured path to simulate the leap.

533
00:32:25,920 --> 00:32:26,800
To fake the jump.

534
00:32:26,800 --> 00:32:27,400
Yes.

535
00:32:27,780 --> 00:32:29,960
We require stable movement.

536
00:32:29,960 --> 00:32:39,280
And this realization that meaning requires movement forces a radical redefinition of what a cognitive representation actually is.

537
00:32:39,540 --> 00:32:42,760
This transitions us perfectly into the philosophical heart of the paper.

538
00:32:43,400 --> 00:32:44,280
Meaning is movement.

539
00:32:44,360 --> 00:32:45,140
It's my favorite part.

540
00:32:45,140 --> 00:32:50,880
We've established that thoughts are trajectories moving through an RSVP field.

541
00:32:52,020 --> 00:33:00,000
They are rafts, navigating currents, constrained by biological speed limits, and the need to avoid vorticity.

542
00:33:00,220 --> 00:33:00,560
Right.

543
00:33:00,940 --> 00:33:07,040
But accepting this completely destroys the traditional understanding of memory and concepts.

544
00:33:07,200 --> 00:33:08,320
It demolishes it.

545
00:33:08,320 --> 00:33:14,920
The traditional view in cognitive science, and certainly in popular culture, is static encoding.

546
00:33:15,240 --> 00:33:15,460
Right.

547
00:33:15,460 --> 00:33:29,460
It's the idea that a concept like dog, or justice, or your childhood home, is encoded as a specific location in the brain, or a specific static pattern of neural activation.

548
00:33:29,460 --> 00:33:31,380
It's the filing cabinet theory.

549
00:33:31,820 --> 00:33:32,260
Exactly.

550
00:33:32,400 --> 00:33:33,780
I have a memory of my 10th birthday.

551
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:36,460
It's in a file folder in a cabinet in my hippocampus.

552
00:33:37,380 --> 00:33:43,460
When I want to remember it, I pull the file out, look at the static JPEG image, and when I'm done, I put it back.

553
00:33:43,740 --> 00:33:46,600
But Flyxion argues vehemently against static encoding.

554
00:33:47,020 --> 00:33:52,000
In a transformation-first, amplet-wist framework, a concept is not a location.

555
00:33:52,460 --> 00:33:55,360
It's not a pattern of activation waiting to be read.

556
00:33:55,520 --> 00:33:58,520
I have to admit, I struggle to let go of the filing cabinet.

557
00:33:58,600 --> 00:33:59,140
We all do.

558
00:33:59,140 --> 00:34:05,240
If I close my eyes right now, and picture my childhood home, I see a static image.

559
00:34:06,180 --> 00:34:07,200
It feels like a file.

560
00:34:07,940 --> 00:34:11,620
If a concept isn't a static file, what on earth is it?

561
00:34:11,780 --> 00:34:17,040
To explain this, the paper introduces a concept called trajectory equivalence, or pi equivalent.

562
00:34:17,180 --> 00:34:17,820
Like a would.

563
00:34:17,960 --> 00:34:28,980
It states that two neural states represent the exact same proposition, only if they behave identically when subjected to the same sequence of cascade perturbations.

564
00:34:29,140 --> 00:34:31,400
Okay, we need to slow down and unpack that.

565
00:34:31,960 --> 00:34:33,140
Behavior under perturbation.

566
00:34:34,140 --> 00:34:35,280
Think about it like this.

567
00:34:35,880 --> 00:34:39,500
Meaning is not about what a state is in isolation.

568
00:34:39,940 --> 00:34:44,500
Meaning is defined by how that state acts when you push it or transform it.

569
00:34:44,600 --> 00:34:45,120
Oh, I see.

570
00:34:45,120 --> 00:34:53,200
The paper draws a direct line here to the philosopher Robert Brandom and his theory of inferential role semantics.

571
00:34:53,540 --> 00:34:54,140
Inferentialism.

572
00:34:54,140 --> 00:35:00,940
Brandom argued that the meaning of a concept is entirely constituted by its role in a network of inferences.

573
00:35:01,180 --> 00:35:03,900
Meaning is use, going back to Wittgenstein.

574
00:35:04,160 --> 00:35:04,560
Yes.

575
00:35:04,560 --> 00:35:12,740
So if I say the sentence, it's raining outside, the meaning of that sentence isn't some abstract dictionary definition hovering in my brain.

576
00:35:12,900 --> 00:35:16,540
The meaning is tied to the physical inferences I can draw from it.

577
00:35:16,540 --> 00:35:24,120
The street will be wet, or I need to grab an umbrella, or the baseball game might be canceled.

578
00:35:24,120 --> 00:35:24,840
Exactly.

579
00:35:25,560 --> 00:35:31,280
But historically, Brandom's inferentialism was purely philosophical.

580
00:35:31,900 --> 00:35:35,140
It was incredibly hard to quantify biologically.

581
00:35:35,380 --> 00:35:36,980
Because you couldn't measure the inferences.

582
00:35:37,160 --> 00:35:37,480
Right.

583
00:35:38,060 --> 00:35:46,360
But Flyxion's Amplitwist framework finally gives inferential semantics a measurable geometric form.

584
00:35:46,460 --> 00:35:46,880
Wow.

585
00:35:46,880 --> 00:35:59,620
Two neural states mean the same thing if, when you apply the exact same Amplitwist operator to both of them, they move in the exact same trajectory through the RSVP field.

586
00:35:59,760 --> 00:36:03,820
So if we take two different people, let's say we put both of us in if I'm warranted machines.

587
00:36:03,980 --> 00:36:04,300
Okay.

588
00:36:04,660 --> 00:36:07,940
I think of the concept of Apple, and you think of the concept of Apple.

589
00:36:07,940 --> 00:36:19,660
Because we have different brains, different genetics, and different childhood memories of Apple's, the static encoding the actual pixels lighting up on the brain scan will look completely different.

590
00:36:19,800 --> 00:36:20,480
Almost certainly.

591
00:36:20,700 --> 00:36:27,580
Under the old filing cabinet theory, it would be a mystery how we are thinking about the same thing, because our files look different.

592
00:36:27,880 --> 00:36:31,820
Under static encoding, the mapping fails entirely.

593
00:36:32,180 --> 00:36:36,580
But under trajectory equivalence, it doesn't matter what the static pixels look like.

594
00:36:36,580 --> 00:36:37,140
Not at all.

595
00:36:37,140 --> 00:36:44,420
Are you saying our thoughts only mean the same thing if our brains react the exact same way when the concept is perturbed?

596
00:36:44,640 --> 00:36:45,000
Yes.

597
00:36:45,280 --> 00:36:56,380
Like, if a researcher says, imagine slicing the apple and both of our neural states smoothly navigate the transition from apple to knife to wedges.

598
00:36:56,560 --> 00:36:56,900
Yes.

599
00:36:57,480 --> 00:36:58,820
That is the core breakthrough.

600
00:36:59,360 --> 00:37:01,740
Meaning, is a verb, not a noun.

601
00:37:02,500 --> 00:37:06,060
It is defined by stability under perturbation.

602
00:37:06,060 --> 00:37:09,560
That is just, it's mind-bending.

603
00:37:09,560 --> 00:37:18,620
In Appendix H, Glickshion mathematically defines a proposition as an equivalence class of perturbation-stable trajectories.

604
00:37:18,960 --> 00:37:22,960
It is a strictly behavioral criterion for semantic content.

605
00:37:23,300 --> 00:37:25,620
So the meaning of a word isn't stored in my head.

606
00:37:25,800 --> 00:37:29,560
The meaning is the way my brain physically moves when the word is pushed.

607
00:37:29,560 --> 00:37:34,040
And this solves a massive mystery in cognitive science and linguistics.

608
00:37:34,180 --> 00:37:34,660
How so?

609
00:37:34,860 --> 00:37:44,460
It explains how human beings can communicate complex, nuanced ideas despite having wildly different brain architectures and personal histories.

610
00:37:44,460 --> 00:37:49,940
My apple neurons and your apple neurons do not need to align spatially.

611
00:37:50,520 --> 00:37:53,240
We don't need to synchronize our static states.

612
00:37:53,380 --> 00:37:55,840
We only need to align our transformations.

613
00:37:56,380 --> 00:37:57,640
We just have to move together.

614
00:37:57,640 --> 00:38:10,260
If your brain and my brain both smoothly navigate the semantic river from apple to pie to baking, with similar phase alignment, we share the meaning.

615
00:38:10,680 --> 00:38:12,200
We are pie equivalent.

616
00:38:12,700 --> 00:38:19,120
We share the geometry of the movement, even if our starting coordinates on the map are thousands of miles apart.

617
00:38:19,240 --> 00:38:19,960
Exactly.

618
00:38:19,960 --> 00:38:26,860
This theory of biological priors, vorticity, and trajectory equivalents is incredibly elegant.

619
00:38:27,120 --> 00:38:28,040
It really is.

620
00:38:28,100 --> 00:38:29,460
But elegance isn't proof.

621
00:38:29,880 --> 00:38:35,680
And what makes this paper so compelling is that Flyxion doesn't just leave it as a philosophical thought experiment.

622
00:38:35,840 --> 00:38:36,840
No, not at all.

623
00:38:36,920 --> 00:38:40,460
The paper shifts from pure theory to empirical prediction.

624
00:38:40,740 --> 00:38:41,000
Right.

625
00:38:41,500 --> 00:38:48,860
Flyxion proposes a highly specific, falsifiable experiment to prove this geometry exists.

626
00:38:48,860 --> 00:38:57,980
And in doing so, the experiment exposes a massive fundamental difference between human cognition and the way we train artificial intelligence.

627
00:38:58,220 --> 00:39:00,920
Specifically, large language models, right?

628
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:01,960
Yes, LLMs.

629
00:39:02,380 --> 00:39:05,240
How do you even begin to test something this abstract?

630
00:39:06,080 --> 00:39:13,940
How do you prove that humans are constrained by a biological prior and that meaning is a trajectory in a laboratory setting?

631
00:39:14,100 --> 00:39:16,840
You have to build a controlled semantic environment.

632
00:39:17,220 --> 00:39:18,140
What does that look like?

633
00:39:18,140 --> 00:39:25,060
Well, if you test people using normal English words, there is too much cultural baggage and memorization involved.

634
00:39:25,220 --> 00:39:26,900
You can't see the raw geometry.

635
00:39:27,140 --> 00:39:29,180
Right, because I already know what an apple is.

636
00:39:29,260 --> 00:39:29,800
Exactly.

637
00:39:30,640 --> 00:39:39,420
So, Flyxion proposes using nonce words, completely made-up words, to test morphological and semantic transformations.

638
00:39:39,680 --> 00:39:40,760
Okay, nonce words.

639
00:39:40,760 --> 00:39:45,140
The experiment is designed around two distinct families of tasks.

640
00:39:46,060 --> 00:39:49,980
Compositional tasks and non-compositional tasks.

641
00:39:49,980 --> 00:39:52,900
Let's break down the compositional tasks first.

642
00:39:52,900 --> 00:39:56,500
These are the tasks that follow the rules of the river, right?

643
00:39:56,700 --> 00:39:59,780
They're smoothly decomposable into logical steps.

644
00:39:59,860 --> 00:40:00,080
Yes.

645
00:40:00,240 --> 00:40:02,680
The paper outlines a specific sequence.

646
00:40:03,180 --> 00:40:04,740
Imagine a made-up root word.

647
00:40:05,800 --> 00:40:06,100
Blick.

648
00:40:06,360 --> 00:40:06,680
Quick.

649
00:40:06,820 --> 00:40:07,000
Okay.

650
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:09,620
That's the starting coordinate on the manifold.

651
00:40:10,220 --> 00:40:14,320
The task requires moving the subject through three layers of transformation.

652
00:40:14,640 --> 00:40:15,220
Layer 1.

653
00:40:15,500 --> 00:40:21,760
Layer 1 requires a phonological change, essentially a scaling of the feature space using the amplitude operator.

654
00:40:21,760 --> 00:40:26,040
So, the subject must transform blick into blicken.

655
00:40:26,640 --> 00:40:27,800
Okay, a simple stretch.

656
00:40:28,120 --> 00:40:28,920
Blick to blicken.

657
00:40:29,400 --> 00:40:32,340
Layer 2 requires a morphological roll rotation.

658
00:40:33,180 --> 00:40:34,560
This is the twist operator.

659
00:40:34,840 --> 00:40:35,420
The twist.

660
00:40:35,580 --> 00:40:40,860
It requires changing the word from a noun to a verb or from an agent to an instrument.

661
00:40:41,380 --> 00:40:43,360
So, blicken becomes blicker.

662
00:40:43,720 --> 00:40:43,900
Yeah.

663
00:40:44,140 --> 00:40:50,200
Finally, layer 3 is a semantic pragmatic shift, which involves the non-linear projection.

664
00:40:50,200 --> 00:40:51,340
The folding of the dough.

665
00:40:51,760 --> 00:40:52,140
Right.

666
00:40:52,380 --> 00:40:57,120
It requires placing the word in context, which is highly entropy-weighted.

667
00:40:57,540 --> 00:41:02,020
So, blicker must be transformed into the concept of a tool for blicking.

668
00:41:02,220 --> 00:41:05,200
So, the full cascade is blick to blicken to blicker.

669
00:41:05,320 --> 00:41:06,200
It's a tool for blicking.

670
00:41:06,420 --> 00:41:09,180
It's a clear, step-by-step, logical sequence.

671
00:41:09,540 --> 00:41:09,980
Stretch.

672
00:41:10,320 --> 00:41:10,620
Twist.

673
00:41:11,080 --> 00:41:11,380
Project.

674
00:41:11,900 --> 00:41:18,420
And crucially, because it is decomposable into those three smooth layers, it perfectly fits

675
00:41:18,420 --> 00:41:20,120
the human biological prior.

676
00:41:20,340 --> 00:41:20,640
Right.

677
00:41:20,800 --> 00:41:21,340
It's safe.

678
00:41:21,340 --> 00:41:27,780
A human brain can map that sequence onto a steady, rhythmic, CPG-like trajectory.

679
00:41:28,720 --> 00:41:33,700
The experimental prediction is that humans navigating this compositional task will show

680
00:41:33,700 --> 00:41:34,800
low vorticity.

681
00:41:35,360 --> 00:41:36,820
Very little cognitive turbulence.

682
00:41:37,040 --> 00:41:37,480
Exactly.

683
00:41:37,900 --> 00:41:42,480
And their phase alignment will actually improve as they move deeper into the cascade.

684
00:41:42,960 --> 00:41:47,760
They will easily find the flow state because the stepping stones are evenly spaced.

685
00:41:47,760 --> 00:41:48,760
Exactly.

686
00:41:48,760 --> 00:41:53,880
But then we have the second family of tasks, the non-compositional tasks.

687
00:41:54,140 --> 00:41:56,360
These are the waterfalls we discussed earlier.

688
00:41:56,440 --> 00:41:56,560
Yeah.

689
00:41:56,700 --> 00:42:02,580
These tasks require massive, discontinuous jumps through the semantic space.

690
00:42:03,300 --> 00:42:08,940
The prompt is designed so that the correct final answer cannot be reached by smoothly

691
00:42:08,940 --> 00:42:11,700
decomposing it into intermediate layers.

692
00:42:11,700 --> 00:42:13,000
There are no stepping stones.

693
00:42:13,220 --> 00:42:13,580
None.

694
00:42:14,100 --> 00:42:18,740
To get the right answer, the system has to leap across a high entropy void.

695
00:42:19,160 --> 00:42:23,840
And based on the biological prior, we know the human brain hates high entropy.

696
00:42:24,100 --> 00:42:24,360
Yeah.

697
00:42:24,460 --> 00:42:26,720
The exponential penalty suppresses the leap.

698
00:42:26,840 --> 00:42:27,160
Right.

699
00:42:27,160 --> 00:42:34,260
So, what does the paper predict human subjects will do when forced to make a non-compositional

700
00:42:34,260 --> 00:42:34,600
leap?

701
00:42:34,760 --> 00:42:37,820
The predicted asymmetry in the paper is fascinating.

702
00:42:38,600 --> 00:42:45,480
It states that on non-compositional tasks, humans will fail, but they will fail directionally.

703
00:42:45,620 --> 00:42:46,200
Directionally.

704
00:42:46,260 --> 00:42:53,560
Because our biology demands a stable, low-dimensional trajectory, the human brain will literally invent

705
00:42:53,560 --> 00:42:56,220
a spurious intermediate stage.

706
00:42:56,220 --> 00:42:57,340
Wait, what?

707
00:42:57,660 --> 00:43:03,640
It will hallucinate a fake stepping stone just to keep the vorticity low and avoid the

708
00:43:03,640 --> 00:43:04,540
entropy penalty.

709
00:43:05,040 --> 00:43:10,340
I absolutely love this concept, the brain inventing fake stepping stones to feel safe.

710
00:43:10,440 --> 00:43:11,160
It's incredible.

711
00:43:11,420 --> 00:43:15,220
When I read this, I instantly thought about how people do mental arithmetic.

712
00:43:15,420 --> 00:43:16,420
Oh, perfect example.

713
00:43:16,420 --> 00:43:24,840
If I ask someone to add 47 and 25, a calculator or an AI without a biological prior just computes

714
00:43:24,840 --> 00:43:26,880
the function and outputs 72.

715
00:43:27,400 --> 00:43:27,960
Instantly.

716
00:43:28,240 --> 00:43:31,300
It's an instant non-compositional leap for a machine.

717
00:43:32,180 --> 00:43:35,600
But my human brain balks at that leap.

718
00:43:35,840 --> 00:43:41,180
The entropy of trying to hold all those numbers and carry the one in a single bound is just too

719
00:43:41,180 --> 00:43:41,520
high.

720
00:43:41,720 --> 00:43:42,340
Too much.

721
00:43:42,340 --> 00:43:44,940
So I invent a spurious intermediate stage.

722
00:43:45,020 --> 00:43:46,360
I break it down into a rhythm.

723
00:43:46,520 --> 00:43:49,940
I say to myself, okay, 40 plus 20 and 60, keep that there.

724
00:43:50,260 --> 00:43:51,820
7 plus 5 is 12.

725
00:43:52,180 --> 00:43:53,700
60 plus 12 is 72.

726
00:43:53,860 --> 00:43:54,080
Right.

727
00:43:54,460 --> 00:44:01,140
I actively force the math onto a slower rhythmic step-by-step grid to make the path feel dynamically

728
00:44:01,140 --> 00:44:01,680
stable.

729
00:44:01,680 --> 00:44:07,200
That is a flawless, everyday example of the biological prior in action.

730
00:44:08,060 --> 00:44:15,280
You sacrificed raw computational efficiency, the instant leap to 72, in order to maintain

731
00:44:15,280 --> 00:44:18,400
geometric stability in your cognitive manifold.

732
00:44:18,560 --> 00:44:20,320
I needed the journey to feel coherent.

733
00:44:20,440 --> 00:44:21,180
You did!

734
00:44:21,620 --> 00:44:23,660
But what about large language models?

735
00:44:24,180 --> 00:44:30,120
How do transformer architectures handle these non-compositional nonce word tasks?

736
00:44:30,120 --> 00:44:33,800
LLMs do not have a biological prior.

737
00:44:34,120 --> 00:44:34,340
